Here is a strict, command-level audit of the "Bazzite Unified Home Server + Gaming Station Guide."

The guide demonstrates an exceptionally high level of Linux engineering. It correctly navigates the complexities of an immutable OS (Fedora Atomic/rpm-ostree), SELinux enforcing modes, rootless/rootful Docker interoperability, and systemd session management. The execution sequence is strictly linear with no circular dependencies.

However, a critical logic flaw in the session management scripts will prevent the core feature (on-demand graphical sessions) from functioning as intended.

🚨 Issue Classification Report
Critical Issues (Execution & Logic Breakers)

SDDM Greeter False-Positive (Phase 8): The loginctl block in the session scripts checks if any session on seat0 is active or online. SDDM’s idle login screen runs as the sddm user and registers as a graphical session with systemd-logind. Because the script does not filter by user or session class, it will detect the idle login screen as an active graphical session, output the ERROR: A graphical session is already active on seat0, and refuse to launch KDE or Gaming Mode.

The Fix: You must filter out the greeter. Update the awk block in both scripts to explicitly require Class=user:

code
Bash
download
content_copy
expand_less
class=$(loginctl show-session "$sid" -p Class --value 2>/dev/null) || continue
if [[ "$class" != "user" ]]; then continue; fi

(Insert this immediately before the if [[ "$seat" == "seat0" ]] check).

Major Issues (System Instability or Deployment Friction)

PowerShell SSH-Key Piping (Phase 4): The command type $env:USERPROFILE\.ssh\id_ed25519.pub | ssh ... "cat >> .ssh/authorized_keys" can fail on older Windows PowerShell versions because type (alias for Get-Content) pipes text with UTF-16LE encoding and CRLF line endings, which corrupts the authorized_keys file on Linux.

The Fix: Advise Windows users to use scp natively: scp $env:USERPROFILE\.ssh\id_ed25519.pub username@192.168.1.50:~/id_ed25519.pub followed by ssh to append it.

Minor Issues (Security Nuances & Efficiency)

Fail2ban Local Subnet Whitelisting (Phase 4): Setting ignoreip = ... 192.168.0.0/16 10.0.0.0/8 explicitly whitelists the entire LAN. If a local IoT device is compromised, it could brute-force the server without being banned. Because PasswordAuthentication no makes brute-forcing mathematically impossible anyway, this is a low risk, but strictly speaking, it weakens internal defense-in-depth.

Redundant Permissions (Phase 8): sudo chown root:root /usr/local/bin/start-kde.sh is redundant. If created using sudo nano as instructed, the file is inherently owned by root. It is harmless, however.

🛠 System State & Environment Verification

Immutable OS Viability: The guide brilliantly uses rpm-ostree override remove podman-docker to resolve Docker-CE conflicts in one atomic transaction. Writing to /usr/local/bin/ is correct, as it is a persistent, mutable overlay (/var/usrlocal/) in Fedora Atomic.

SELinux Integrity: Pre-labeling the Nextcloud mount point (semanage fcontext) before applying restorecon is the correct approach. Using security_opt: - label:disable for the Nextcloud AIO master container is securely executed and mandatory for socket access on Fedora.

SSH & Firewall Order of Operations: Phase 4 correctly secures port 53222 in SELinux before reloading SSH, and removes port 22 from firewalld only after verifying connectivity on the new port. This eliminates the risk of a lockout.

NAT Loopback (Phase 10): Binding the AIO Apache container to 127.0.0.1:11000 while utilizing Docker's internal DNS (nextcloud-aio-apache) for Nginx Proxy Manager is functionally flawless. It secures the backend from direct LAN access while allowing the proxy full access.

📋 Content Assessment (Essential vs. Optional)

Essential: nofail in fstab (bricks headless systems if omitted), SELinux semanage configurations, rpm-ostree commands, SSH Drop-in config, Docker log rotation (Docker fills OS drives rapidly without it).

Optional: Home Assistant Integration (Appendix C), krdp setup (Phase 9 - completely optional if the user only intends to use the machine as a media/gaming device via HDMI), Nextcloud setup (Phases 7/10).

Unnecessary: None. The guide contains zero "bloat." Every command directly contributes to a secure, stable, or recoverable system state.

✅ Final Validation Checklist

To confirm the system has successfully reached the intended, secure, production-ready state, execute these verifications:

Network Security: Run sudo firewall-cmd --list-all. Confirm only 53222/tcp is listed under ports. (80 and 443 are handled by Docker's iptables rules).

SELinux State: Run sudo semanage port -l | grep ssh. Confirm ssh_port_t tcp 53222 is registered. Run ls -Z /srv/nextcloud-data and confirm the container_file_t context is applied.

Daemon Isolation: Run docker ps. Confirm all Nextcloud, NPM, and DuckDNS containers show a status of Up. Run sudo fail2ban-client status sshd and confirm it is actively monitoring port 53222.

Session Determinism: (After applying the Class=user fix) Execute ssh -p 53222 user@ip 'sudo start-kde.sh'. Confirm the terminal returns immediately, no output is hung, and the physical display transitions from the SDDM greeter to KDE Plasma.

Headless Resilience: Reboot the server. Run cat /etc/sddm.conf.d/zzz-headless-server.conf and confirm the file persists with empty User= and Session= values.

